Hey @everyonesdesign,

This is not supported at the moment. I would love to support this use case but I am not using this feature of Draft.js in my editor implementation, so I can't commit to implementing it myself any time soon. That said, I'm very happy to discuss and review a PR if you are keen to implement it yourself.

Here is what it could look like, following the API of entity decorators:

```python
class LI:
    def render(self, props):
        # Not sure whether data is the right name for this key, or "metadata" or "block_data".
        # Ideally this should be aligned on the React props.
        data = props.get('data')
        return DOM.create_element('li')

config = {
    'entity_decorators': {
        ENTITY_TYPES.LINK: Link(),
    },
    'block_map': dict(BLOCK_MAP, **{
        BLOCK_TYPES.UNORDERED_LIST_ITEM: {
            'element': LI(),
            'wrapper': ['ul', {'className': 'bullet-list'}],
        },
    }),
}

exporter = HTML(config)
```

To implement this, I think it could be enough to change https://github.com/springload/draftjs_exporter/blob/master/draftjs_exporter/wrapper_state.py#L131 to pass the block's `data` as a prop. You could try it yourself by changing this one line to:

```python
elt = DOM.create_element(options.element[0], block.get('data'))
```

Then the next step would be figuring out how this works with the different block map formats documented here: https://github.com/springload/draftjs_exporter/blob/master/draftjs_exporter/wrapper_state.py#L23.

Finally I would probably want to make sure that `wrapper` supports this too, but that doesn't have to happen at the same time.

Now the reason I'm not using this / supporting this at the moment is because I haven't found good enough documentation on block-level metadata (what it's meant for) to risk relying on it. Do you have any good resources on the topic?

